ModuleInfo.Description:
This module executes a list of Emme Tools in sequence, at four different points of the Model System execution:
  • ModelSystem Setup: These tools are executed before any zonal information is loaded.
  • Initial Run: These tools are executed prior to the first outer-loop iteration but after the zonal data has been loaded.
  • Iteration: These tools are executed once per iteration as the last step.
  • Final Iteration: These tools are executed after all of the iterations have been completed.

This module loads a series of data in order to provide demographic data about a zone system. 
This one in particular takes the data for planning districts and then applies them across the zone system using 
the data loaded in from zone system module. The root module of the model system is required to be of 
type ITravelDemandModel.

Copy of 'Aggreagted Demographics Data'. This is module is a quick-and-dirty demographics module - a generic one will be implemented in the near future. Currently as a result of constraints in the code for this module, employment categories and employment status categories are hard-coded. All file formats remain the same with one exception: all files are assumed to have a single header line with column labels, and lines beginning with '//' will be skipped.

ModuleInfo.Description:
This module provides one of the basic types of purposes used by GTAModel. 
An assignment purpose is similar to any in a four step model however the generation and distribution 
step have been fused since they work at an individual agent level. The AssignmentPurpose module takes 
in an IAssignment sub-module, a list of IDemographicCategory modules and an IUtilityModifyModeSplit module.
This module requires the root module of the model system to be an ‘I4StepModel’.

This module is responsible for selecting a specific segment of the population based upon a range of ages, what type of work they have, employment status, and mobility category. It also provides parameters to change how the mode split will be placed upon them. You can disable particular modes with the ‘Infeasible Modes’ parameter by entering in the mode’s name. In addition you can also modify the utility of the mode by entering in its name, a colon and then entering in a number. You can chain these together by adding commas between them. This module generates the trips based upon the population living in zones and the amount of retail employment in the destination zones. This module requires the root module of the model system to be an ‘IDemographic4StepModelSystemTemplate’.

ModuleInfo.Description:
The Model System Template for GTAModel V2/2.5 based Models. This module is the root module for GTAModel. It requires an IZoneSystem, IDemographicsData, 
a list of INetworkData, a list of IModeChoiceNode, an INetworkAssignment, a list of IPurpose, an 
IPopulation, and finally a list of ISelfContainedModule for running at the end of the model system. 
Optionally it can also take in 2 other ISelfContainedModule, one for assigning work zones and another 
for assigning school zones.

This module is designed to distribute out the GTAModel version 3 home based other trips. It is also compatible with the version 2 of GTAModel by specifying all of the employment parameters to be the same value for the regions. The equation for the systematic utility is as follows:

V_ij= (〖TravelTime〗_R 〖AutoTime〗_ij )

+ (〖PopulationParameter〗_R (ln⁡〖〖Population〗_j 〗 ))

+ (〖ProfessionalParameter〗_R (ln⁡〖〖ProfessionalEmployment〗_j 〗 ))

+ (〖GeneralParameter〗_R (ln⁡〖〖GeneralEmployment〗_j 〗 ))

+ (〖SalesParameter〗_R (ln⁡〖〖SalesEmployment〗_j 〗 ))

+(〖ManufacturingParameter〗_R (ln⁡〖〖Manufacturing〗_j 〗 ))

Where i is the origin zone and j is the destination zone. R represents the region of the origin.

Population Assignment is the fusion of a generation and a distribution algorithm.

try to find a property of the given name and use that to load the zones to assign to.
This module requires the root module of the model system to be of type ‘IDemographicsModelSystemTemplate’.

ModuleInfo.Description:
The Log-Sum Distribution module is designed to rapidly apply go through different
demographic categories and build demand matrices for them.  Primarily designed 
for building Place of Residence Place of Work models this module will work anywhere 
where you want a Logsum of the mode choice to represent the friction values.  There is an 
optional sub-module available for loading in K-Factors.  This module also supports using the 
GPU to enhance the processing time of the model.

ModuleInfo.Description:
A basic, no-frills Emme transit assignment tool. Saves transit strategies to the databank for future analysis (e.g., extraction of travel times matrix - see tools in TMG.GTAModel.NetworkAnalysis).

Boarding penalties are assigned to transit lines, and are assumed to be already defined in UT3.

Generates a hyper-network to support fare-based transit assignment(FBTA), from an XML schema file.Links and segments with negative fare values will be reported to the Logbook for further inspection. For fare schema specification, please consult TMG documentation.

Temporary storage requirements: one transit line extra attribute, one node extra attribute.
ModuleInfo.Name: Build Fare Based Transit Network From Schema

ModuleInfo.Description:
Generates a hyper-network to support fare-based transit assignment(FBTA), from an XML schema file.Links and segments with negative fare values will be reported to the Logbook for further inspection. For fare schema specification, please consult TMG documentation.

Temporary storage requirements: one transit line extra attribute, one node extra attribute.
ModuleInfo.Name: Build Fare Based Transit Network From Schema

ModuleInfo.Description: Calculates a per-km link toll attribute in Emnme, assuming a two-zone system
Loads a scenario and checks that all referenced functions (link VDF, transit segment TTF, and turn TPF) are defined in the emmebank. It will raise an error listing all missing functions.
Basic tool for extracting matrix results from Emme. This module is considered deprecated after Emme 4.04
ModuleInfo.Name: Export EMME Matrix To File

ModuleInfo.Description:
Assigns a limited matrix of demand to centroids which represent
                             GO train stations. Can assign a scalar matrix of 0 or a full matrix of
                             demand (constrained by the station selector). Unlike most other transit
                             assignment tools, this tool saves the constrained IVTT and wait times
                             matrices as outputs.

Executes a congested transit assignment procedure for GTAModel V4.0.

Hard-coded assumptions:
  • Boarding penalties are assumed stored in UT3
  • The congestion term is stored in US3
  • In-vehicle time perception is 1.0
  • Unless specified, all available transit modes will be used.
This tool is only compatible with Emme 4 and later versions
ModuleInfo.Name: V4 Fare Based Transit Assignment (FBTA)

ModuleInfo.Description:
Executes a congested transit assignment procedure for GTAModel V4.0.

Hard-coded assumptions:
  • Boarding penalties are assumed stored in UT3
  • The congestion term is stored in US3
  • In-vehicle time perception is 1.0
  • Unless specified, all available transit modes will be used.
This tool is only compatible with Emme 4 and later versions
Executes a transit assignment which can accumulate fares.
ModuleInfo.Name: Fare Based Emme Transit Assignment

ModuleInfo.Description: Basic tool for extracting matrix results from Emme. This module is considered deprecated after Emme 4.04
ModuleInfo.Name: Export Matrix From Emme

ModuleInfo.Description:
Executes a fare-based transit assignment (FBTA) as described in the GTAModel Version 3 documentation: Using special functions on centroid connectors and transit time functions. This requires a compatible network, which can currently only be created by macro_EditNetwork.mac.

This Tool can also be used to execute a more standard tranist assignment procedure by using a fare perception of '0'. This Tool executes an Extended Transit Assignment, which allows for subsequent analyses; such as those that can be found in TMG2.Assignment.TransitAnalysis.
ModuleInfo.Name: Legacy Fare-Based Transit Assignment

ModuleInfo.Description: Executes a standard Emme road assignment using tolls for link dis-utility; including a second 'all-or-nothing' assignment to recover link costs. A temporary link attribute is used to store link toll actual costs on links with VDF = 14 or VDF = 15. This is converted to generalized cost using the Toll Perception Factor parameter.
ModuleInfo.Name: Toll Based Emme Road Assignment

ModuleInfo.Description:
NOT IMPLEMENTED
Exports traffic assignment results on links flagged with a countpost number.

Extracts average in-vehicle, walking, waiting, boarding time, and cost matrices from a legacy fare-based assignment. Matrices will be multiplied by a feasibility matrices (where 0 = infeasible and 1 = feasible).

Produces a report of various transit line attributes, saved to a comma-separated-values (CSV) table format. Transit line results can be optionally aggregated using a two-column correspondence table, with the first column referenced to Emme transit line IDs.

For each transit line (or line grouping), the following attributes are exported:
  • Number of Emme routes (branches) in the line (=1 if no aggregation)
  • Total line boardings
  • Line peak volume
  • Line peak volume/capacity ratio
  • Weighted average of volume/capacity ratio

Extracts real (raw) transit in-vehicle times matrix from any type of Extended Transit Assignment.In particular, this tool auto - detects if a congested or capacitated assignment has been run and compensates for the additional crowding term.

Produces a table indicating which zones are within a 1km (or other user-specified distance) from subway or GO train stations. Subway stations are identified as stops of lines with mode = 'm'. GO stations can be identified in one of two ways:
  1. Station centroids, identified by a node selector expression; or
  2. Stops of lines with mode = 'r'.
This data is saved into a CSV file with three columns: 'Zone', 'NearSubway' , 'NearGO'. The first column identifies the zone, the second column indicates whether a zone is within the radius of a subway station (0 or 1), and the third column indicates whether a zone is within the radius of a GO Train station (0 or 1). Zones not in the radius of either are not listed.

This tool loads Screenlines from a shapefile and then determineswhich links intersect the screenline's geometry. This tool then exports the volume crossing each element of the screenline and in each direction on that link into a CSV file. The shapefile's attribute table must contain fields labeled 'Id', 'Descr' 'PosDirName' and 'NegDirName'. Results are written to a text file. Results will only be reported for the modes selected by the user.
ModuleInfo.Name: Report Screenline Results

ModuleInfo.Description: Extracts average total cost (fares) matrix from a fare-based transit assignment,assuming that operator-access fares are stored on walk links in '@tfare', and that in-line orzonal fares are stored in 'us3'.
ModuleInfo.Name: Extract Cost Matrix

ModuleInfo.Description: Extracts a feasibility matrix (where 1 is feasible and 0 is infeasible), based on cut-off values for walking, waiting, and total times.
ModuleInfo.Name: Extract Feasibility Matrix

ModuleInfo.Description: Extracts average in-vehicle, walking, waiting, and boarding timematrices from a strategy-based assignment.
ModuleInfo.Name: Extract Transit Travel Time Matrices

ModuleInfo.Description: Flags certain premium bus lines by assigning '1' to line extra attribute '@lflag'. Initializes  @lflag to 0 first.
ModuleInfo.Name: Flag Premium Buses

ModuleInfo.Description: Imports boarding penalties into UT3 (line attribute 3) from a file. The file is delimited by ';' and contain the headers 'boarding_penalty' and 'filter_expression'. The 'boarding_penalty' column indicates an applied peanlty to be stored in UT3, while the 'filter_expression' indicates the expression used by the Emme Matrix Calculator to filter transit lines.
ModuleInfo.Name: Import V3 Boarding Penalties

ModuleInfo.Description: Extracts average in-vehicle, walking, waiting, and boarding time matrices from a strategy-based assignment, for matrices flagged by attribute @lflag. /r/n/r/nTo calculate costs, the network must have transfer fares stored in @tfare and in-line fares stored in us3.
ModuleInfo.Name: Select Line Analyses

ModuleInfo.Description:
Executes a station-to-station assignment for commuter rail (GO Transit) using optional fare-based impedances. Similar to Legacy FBTA, this assignment uses functions to apply fare impedances.
 Saves matrix results for in-vehicle times and costs (fares) for feasible trips from station centroids only. Station centroids are hard-coded to NCS11 definitions.
ModuleInfo.Name: Legacy Station-to-Station Assignment

ModuleInfo.Description: This module provides floating point data segmented by origin and destination planning districts.

This module is designed to read in .txt formats or .csv formats.  
It works be reading in the first four ‘columns’, where they could be separated by spaces, 
tabs, or commas.  It also tries to read in the standard header (an example is given in the ReadODTextData module).  
What makes this module different from the ReadODTextData is that it will filter out records based 
on the third column instead of returning all of the records.  This is useful when implementing the 
Non-Work/School trips to be able to filter out by occupation type.

This module provides the ability to read OD data from .txt formats or .csv formats. It works by reading in the first three “columns”, where they could be separated by spaces, or tabs, or commas. It also tries to read in the standard

-----------------

My Header, some information about the data

--------------------------

headers and ignore them. If one of these headers is not present or the header parameter is set it will skip the first line so that standard csv data will also work.

This module is designed to read in .txt formats or .csv formats.  
It works be reading in the first two ‘columns’, where they could be separated by spaces, 
tabs, or commas.  It also tries to read in the standard header (an example is given in the 
ReadODTextData module).  What makes this module different from the ReadODTextData is that ignore 
the destination data. Instead the first column will be the origin and the second column will be the data.

The goal of this class is to provide a dynamic way of reading in csv data.  
The expected format is a number of header lines, given in as a parameter.  Following that it is 
expecting the first two columns to represent the indexes of the first two dimensions.  
The third dimension is expressed by its “Data-column Sparse Space” parameter and the reading 
of that data in the columns that follow along in the row.  These columns are then linked to sparse 
spaces by referencing each column to the parameter, thusly the number of columns for data are expected 
to be the same as in the parameter.
